# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: supabase-platform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] Web and mobile apps require a similar set of features on the backend, including notification service, integration with social networks, and cloud storage.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] Each of these services has its own API that must be individually incorporated into an app, a process that can be time-consuming and complicated for app developers.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers form a bridge between the frontend of an application and various cloud-based backends via a unified API and SDK.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] Providing a consistent way to manage backend data means that developers do not need to redevelop their own backend for each of the services that their apps need to access, potentially saving both time and money.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers offer different set of features and backend tools.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers also come in different types, suiting developers of different needs.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] Most BaaS providers host backend platforms on their cloud servers.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] They also manage the infrastructure, security, and scalability of the platforms.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] Developers can access the backend services via a web interface or the provided APIs.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] Some examples of cloud-based BaaS include Firebase (hosted on Google Cloud Platform), AWS Amplify (hosted on Amazon Web Services), and Microsoft Azure Mobile Apps (hosted on Microsoft Azure).
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] Self-hosted BaaS allow developers to host backend on their own servers, providing more flexibility and potential to customization compared to cloud-based BaaS, which often is more difficult to migrate from.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] However, developers are also in charge of managing the infrastructure, security, and scalability of their servers.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] Mobile backend as a service (MBaaS) is a type of BaaS specifically for applications deployed in mobile systems.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] While some references use MBaaS interchangeably for BaaS, BaaS can have a wider variety of support such as for web apps and desktop apps.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] BaaS providers generate revenue from their services in various ways, often using a freemium model.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] Under this model, a client receives a certain number of free active users or API calls per month, and pays a fee for each user or call over this limit.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] Alternatively, clients can pay a set fee for a package which allows for a greater number of calls or active users per month.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] There are also flat fee plans that make the pricing more predictable.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] Some of the providers offer the unlimited API calls inside their free plan offerings.
[src:supabase-platform/backend-as-a-service] Another business model that has been used by a lot of BaaS providers is PAYG (pay as you go), which has a flexible cost based on developers' usage of database, storage, bandwidth, function calls, user numbers etc.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Open-source software development can bring in diverse perspectives beyond those of a single company.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] A 2024 estimate of the value of open-source software to firms is $8.8 trillion, as firms would need to spend 3.5 times the amount they currently do without the use of open source software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The Open Source Initiative's (OSI) definition is recognized by several governments internationally as the standard or *de facto* definition.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] OSI uses *The Open Source Definition* to determine whether it considers a software license open source.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The definition was based on the Debian Free Software Guidelines, written and adapted primarily by Bruce Perens.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Perens did not base his writing on the "four freedoms" from the Free Software Foundation (FSF), which were only widely available later.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Under Perens' definition, *open source* is a broad software license that makes source code available to the general public with relaxed or non-existent restrictions on the use and modification of the code.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] It is an explicit "feature" of open source that it puts very few restrictions on the use or distribution by any organization or user, in order to enable the rapid evolution of the software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Despite initially accepting it, Richard Stallman of the FSF now flatly opposes the term "Open Source" being applied to what they refer to as "free software".
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Although he agrees that the two terms describe "almost the same category of software", Stallman considers equating the terms incorrect and misleading.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Stallman also opposes the professed pragmatism of the Open Source Initiative, as he fears that the free software ideals of freedom and community are threatened by compromising on the FSF's idealistic standards for software freedom.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The FSF considers free software to be a subset of open-source software, and Richard Stallman explained that DRM software, for example, can be developed as open source, despite that it does not give its users freedom (it restricts them), and thus does not qualify as free software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In his 1997 essay *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*, open-source influential contributor Eric S.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Raymond suggests a model for developing OSS known as the *bazaar* model.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Raymond likens the development of software by traditional methodologies to building a cathedral, with careful isolated work by individuals or small groups.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] He suggests that all software should be developed using the bazaar style, with differing agendas and approaches.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In the traditional model of development, which he called the *cathedral* model, development takes place in a centralized way.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Roles include people dedicated to designing (the architects), people responsible for managing the project, and people responsible for implementation.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Traditional software engineering follows the cathedral model.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The bazaar model, however, is different.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In this model, roles are not clearly defined.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The process of Open source development begins with a requirements elicitation where developers consider if they should add new features or if a bug needs to be fixed in their project.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] This is established by communicating with the OSS community through avenues such as bug reporting and tracking or mailing lists and project pages.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Next, OSS developers select or are assigned to a task and identify a solution.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Because there are often many different possible routes for solutions in OSS, the best solution must be chosen with careful consideration and sometimes even peer feedback.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The developer then begins to develop and commit the code.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The code is then tested and reviewed by peers.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Developers can edit and evolve their code through feedback from continuous integration.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Once the leadership and community are satisfied with the whole project, it can be partially released and user instruction can be documented.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] If the project is ready to be released, it is frozen, with only serious bug fixes or security repairs occurring.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Finally, the project is fully released and only changed through minor bug fixes.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Open source implementation of a standard can increase the adoption and long-term viability of that standard.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] It often fosters developer loyalty, as contributors feel a greater sense of participation and ownership in the development process and the end product.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Moreover, lower costs of marketing and logistical services are needed for OSS.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] OSS can be a tool to promote a company's image, including its commercial products.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The OSS development approach has been known to some to help produce reliable, high quality software quickly and inexpensively.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Open source development offers the potential to quicken innovation and create social value.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In France, for instance, a policy that incentivized government to favor free open-source software increased to nearly 600,000 OSS contributions per year, generating social value by increasing the quantity and quality of open-source software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] This policy also led to an estimated increase of up to 18% of tech startups and a 14% increase in the number of people employed in the IT sector.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] OSS can be highly reliable when it has thousands of independent programmers testing and fixing bugs of the software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Open source is not dependent on the company or author that originally created it.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Even if the company fails, the code continues to exist and be developed by its users.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] OSS is flexible as modular systems allow programmers to build custom interfaces or add new abilities to it.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The mix of divergent perspectives, corporate objectives, and personal goals allows innovation.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Moreover, free software can be developed in accordance with purely technical requirements.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] It does not require thinking about commercial pressure that often degrades the quality of the software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Commercial pressures make traditional software developers pay more attention to customers' requirements than to security requirements, since such features are somewhat invisible to the customer.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In open-source software development, tools are used to support the development of the product and the development process itself.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Version control systems such as Centralized Version control system (CVCS) and the distributed version control system (DVCS) are examples of tools, often open source, that help manage the source code files and the changes to those files for a software project in order to foster collaboration.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] CVCS are centralized with a central repository while DVCS are decentralized and have a local repository for every user.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Concurrent Versions System (CVS) and later Subversion (SVN) are examples of CVCS, whereas Git is a DVCS and the most widely used version control software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The repositories are hosted and published on source-code-hosting facilities such as GitHub or Gitlab.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Open-source projects use utilities such as issue trackers to organize open-source software development.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Commonly used bug trackers include Bugzilla and Redmine.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Tools such as mailing lists and IRC provide means of coordination and discussion of bugs among developers.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Project web pages, wiki pages, roadmap lists and newsgroups allow for the distribution of project information that focuses on end users.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The basic roles OSS participants can fall into multiple categories, beginning with leadership at the center of the project who have control over its execution.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Next are the core contributors with a great deal of experience and authority in the project who may guide the other contributors.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Non-core contributors have less experience and authority, but regularly contribute and are vital to the project's development.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] New contributors are the least experienced but with mentorship and guidance can become regular contributors.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Some possible ways of contributing to open-source software include such roles as programming, maintaining, user interface design and testing, web design, bug triage, accessibility design and testing, UX design, code testing, and security review and testing.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However, there are several ways of contributing to OSS projects even without coding skills.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] For example, some less technical ways of participating are documentation writing and editing, translation, project management, event organization and coordination, marketing, release management, community management, and public relations and outreach.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Funding is another way that individuals and organizations choose to contribute to open source projects.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Groups like Open Collective provide a means for individuals to contribute monthly to supporting their favorite projects.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Organizations like the Sovereign Tech Fund is able to contribute to millions to supporting the tools the German Government uses.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The National Science Foundation established a Pathways to Enable Open-Source Ecosystems (POSE) program to support open source innovation.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The adoption of open-source software by industry is increasing over time.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] OSS is popular in several industries such as telecommunications, aerospace, healthcare, and media & entertainment due to the benefits it provides.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Adoption of OSS is more likely in larger organizations and is dependent on the company's IT usage, operating efficiencies, and the productivity of employees.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Industries are likely to use OSS due to back-office functionality, sales support, research and development, software features, quick deployment, portability across platforms and avoidance of commercial license management.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Additionally, lower cost for hardware and ownership are also important benefits.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Organizations that contribute to the development and expansions of free and open-source software movements exist all over the world.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] These organizations are dedicated to goals such as teaching and spreading technology.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] As listed by a former vice president of the Open Source Initiative, some American organizations include the Free Software Foundation, Software Freedom Conservancy, the Open Source Initiative and Software in the Public Interest.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Within Europe some notable organizations are Free Software Foundation Europe, open-source projects EU (OSP) and OpenForum Europe (OFE).
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] One Australian organization is Linux Australia while Asia has Open source Asia and FOSSAsia.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Free and open source software for Africa (FOSSFA) and OpenAfrica are African organizations and Central and South Asia has such organizations as FLISOL and GRUP de usuarios de software libre Peru.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Outside of these, many more organizations dedicated to the advancement of open-source software exist.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] FOSS products are generally licensed under two types of licenses: permissive licensing and copyleft licensing.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Both of these types of licenses are different than proprietary licensing in that they can allow more users access to the software and allow for the creation of derivative works as specified by the terms of the specific license, as each license has its own rules.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Permissive licenses allow recipients of the software to implement the author's copyright rights without having to use the same license for distribution.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Examples of this type of license include the BSD, MIT, and Apache licenses.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Copyleft licenses are different in that they require recipients to use the same license for at least some parts of the distribution of their works.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Strong copyleft licenses require all derivative works to use the same license while weak copyleft licenses require the use of the same license only under certain conditions.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Examples of this type of license include the GNU family of licenses, and the MPL and EPL licenses.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The similarities between these two categories of licensing include that they provide a broad grant of copyright rights, require that recipients preserve copyright notices, and that a copy of the license is provided to recipients with the code.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] One important legal precedent for open-source software was created in 2008, when the Jacobson v Katzer case enforced terms of the Artistic license, including attribution and identification of modifications.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The ruling of this case cemented enforcement under copyright law when the conditions of the license were not followed.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Because of the similarity of the Artistic license to other open-source software licenses, the ruling created a precedent that applied widely.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Examples of free-software license / open-source licenses include Apache licenses, BSD licenses, GNU General Public Licenses, GNU Lesser General Public License, MIT License, Eclipse Public License and Mozilla Public License.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Several gray areas exist within software regulation that have great impact on open-source software, such as if software is a good or service, what can be considered a modification, governance through contract vs license, ownership and right of use.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] While there have been developments on these issues, they often lead to even more questions.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The existence of these uncertainties in regulation has a negative impact on industries involved in technologies as a whole.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Within the legal history of software as a whole, there was much debate on whether to protect it as intellectual property under patent law, copyright law or establishing a unique regulation.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Ultimately, copyright law became the standard with computer programs being considered a form of literary work, with some tweaks of unique regulation.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Software is generally considered source code and object code, with both being protectable, though there is legal variety in this definition.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Some jurisdictions attempt to expand or reduce this conceptualization for their own purposes.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] For example, The European Court of Justice defines a computer program as not including the functionality of a program, the programming language, or the format of data files.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] By limiting protections of the different aspects of software, the law favors an open-source approach to software use.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The US especially has an open approach to software, with most open-source licenses originating there.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However, this has increased the focus on patent rights within these licenses, which has seen backlash from the OSS community, who prefer other forms of IP protection.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Another issue includes technological protection measures (TPM) and digital rights management (DRM) techniques which were internationally legally recognized and protected in the 1996 World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) Treaty.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Open source software proponents disliked these technologies as they constrained end-users potentially beyond copyright law.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Europe responded to such complaints by putting TPM under legal controls, representing a victory for OSS supporters.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In open-source communities, instead of owning the software produced, the producer owns the development of the evolving software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In this way, the future of the software is open, making ownership or intellectual property difficult within OSS.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Licensing and branding can prevent others from stealing it, preserving its status as a public good.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Open source software can be considered a public good as it is available to everyone and does not decrease in value for others when downloaded by one person.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Open source software is unique in that it becomes more valuable as it is used and contributed to, instead of diminishing the resource.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] This is explained by concepts such as investment in reputation and network effects.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The economic model of open-source software can be explained as developers contribute work to projects, creating public benefits.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Developers choose projects based on the perceived benefits or costs, such as improved reputation or value of the project.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The motivations of developers can come from many different places and reasons, but the important takeaway is that money is not the only or even most important incentivization.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Because economic theory mainly focuses on the consumption of scarce resources, the OSS dynamic can be hard to understand.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In OSS, producers become consumers by reaping the rewards of contributing to a project.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] For example, a developer becomes well regarded by their peers for a successful contribution to an OSS project.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The social benefits and interactions of OSS are difficult to account for in economic models as well.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Furthermore, the innovation of technology creates constantly changing value discussions and outlooks, making economic model unable to predict social behavior.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Although OSS is theoretically challenging in economic models, it is explainable as a sustainable social activity that requires resources.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] These resources include time, money, technology and contributions.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Many developers have used technology funded by organizations such as universities and governments, though these same organizations benefit from the work done by OSS.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] As OSS grows, hybrid systems containing OSS and proprietary systems are becoming more common.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Throughout the mid 2000s, more and more tech companies have begun to use OSS.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] For example, Dell's move of selling computers with Linux already installed.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Microsoft itself has launched a Linux-based operating system despite previous animosity with the OSS movement.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Despite these developments, these companies tend to only use OSS for certain purposes, leading to worries that OSS is being taken advantage of by corporations and not given anything in return.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However, an issue to be considered is cybersecurity.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] While accidental vulnerabilities are possible, so are attacks by outside agents.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Because of these fears, governmental interest in contributing to the governance of software has become more prominent.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However, these are the broad strokes of the issue, with each country having their own specific politicized interactions with open-source software and their goals for its implementation.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] These criteria include whether it comes from and is maintained by trusted sources, whether it will continue to be maintained, if there are dependencies on sub-components in the software, component security and integrity, and foreign governmental influence.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Another issue for governments in regard to open source is their investments in technologies such as operating systems, semiconductors, cloud, and artificial intelligence.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] These technologies all have implications for global cooperation, again opening up security issues and political consequences.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Many countries have to balance technological innovation with technological dependence in these partnerships.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] For example, after China's open-source dependent company Huawei was prevented from using Google's Android system in 2019, they began to create their own alternative operating system: Harmony OS.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Germany recently established a Sovereign Tech Fund, to help support the governance and maintenance of the software that they use.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In the early days of computing, particularly during the 1950s and 1960s, programmers and developers commonly shared software to learn from one another and advance the field.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Early systems such as Unix even provided users with access to their source code, allowing collaboration and modification.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However, with the rise of the commercial software industry in the 1970s and 1980s, this culture of open sharing began to decline as proprietary models became dominant.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Despite this shift, academic and research institutions continued to promote collaborative software development practices.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In response, the open-source movement was born out of the work of skilled programmer enthusiasts, widely referred to as hackers or hacker culture.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] One of these enthusiasts, Richard Stallman, was a driving force behind the free software movement, which would later allow for the open-source movement.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In 1984, he resigned from MIT to create a free operating system, GNU, after the programmer culture in his lab was stifled by proprietary software preventing source code from being shared and improved upon.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] GNU was UNIX compatible, meaning that the programmer enthusiasts would still be familiar with how it worked.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However, it quickly became apparent that there was some confusion with the label Stallman had chosen of free software, which he described as free as in free speech, not free beer, referring to the meaning of free as freedom rather than price.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] He later expanded this concept of freedom to the four essential freedoms.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Through GNU, open-source norms of incorporating others' source code, community bug fixes and suggestions of code for new features appeared.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In 1985, Stallman founded the Free Software Foundation (FSF) to promote changes in software and to help write GNU.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In order to prevent his work from being used in proprietary software, Stallman created the concept of copyleft, which allowed the use of his work by anyone, but under specific terms.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] To do this, he created the GNU General Public License (GNU GPL) in 1989, which was updated in 1991.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In 1991, GNU was combined with the Linux kernel written by Linus Torvalds, as a kernel was missing in GNU.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The operating system is now usually referred to as Linux.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] As free software developed, the Free Software Foundation began to look how to bring free software ideas and perceived benefits to the commercial software industry.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] It was concluded that FSF's social activism was not appealing to companies and they needed a way to rebrand the free software movement to emphasize the business potential of sharing and collaborating on software source code.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The term open source was suggested by Christine Peterson in 1998 at a meeting of supporters of free software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Many in the group felt the name free software was confusing to newcomers and holding back industry interest and they readily accepted the new designation of open source, creating the Open Source Initiative (OSI) and the OSI definition of what open source software is.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The Open Source Initiative's (OSI) definition is now recognized by several governments internationally as the standard or *de facto* definition.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The OSI definition differed from the free software definition in that it allows the inclusion of proprietary software and allows more liberties in its licensing.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Some, such as Stallman, agree more with the original concept of free software as a result because it takes a strong moral stance against proprietary software, though there is much overlap between the two movements in terms of the operation of the software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However, while free and open-source software (FOSS) has historically played a role outside of mainstream private software development, companies as large as Microsoft have begun to develop official open source presences on the Internet.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] IBM, Oracle, and State Farm are just a few of the companies with a serious public stake in today's competitive open source market, marking a significant shift in the corporate philosophy concerning the development of FOSS.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The future of the open source software community, and the free software community by extension, has become successful if not confused about what it stands for.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] For example, Android and Ubuntu are examples milestones of success in the open source software rise to prominence from the sidelines of technological innovation as it existed in the early 2000s.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The use of OSS has become more common in business with 78% of companies reporting that they run all or part of their operations on FOSS.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The popularity of OSS has risen to the point that Microsoft, a once detractor of OSS, has included its use in their systems.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However, this success has raised concerns that will determine the future of OSS as the community must answer questions such as what OSS is, what should it be, and what should be done to protect it, if it even needs protecting.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] All in all, while the free and open source revolution has slowed to a perceived equilibrium in the market place, that does not mean it is over as many theoretical discussions must take place to determine its future.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Open source software differs from proprietary software in that it is publicly available, the license requires no fees, modifications and distributions are allowed under license specifications.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] All of this works to prevent a monopoly on any OSS product, which is a goal of proprietary software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Proprietary software limits their customers' choices to either committing to using that software, upgrading it or switching to other software, forcing customers to have their software preferences impacted by their monetary cost.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The ideal case scenario for the proprietary software vendor would be a lock-in, where the customer does not or cannot switch software due to these costs and continues to buy products from that vendor.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Within proprietary software, bug fixes can only be provided by the vendor, moving platforms requires another purchase and the existence of the product relies on the vendor, who can discontinue it at any point.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Additionally, proprietary software does not provide its source code and cannot be altered by users.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] For businesses, this can pose a security risk and source of frustration, as they cannot specialize the product to their needs, and there may be hidden threats or information leaks within the software that they cannot access or change.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Under OSI's definition, open source is a broad software license that makes source code available to the general public with relaxed or non-existent restrictions on the use and modification of the code.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] It is an explicit feature of open source that it puts very few restrictions on the use or distribution by any organization or user, in order to enable the rapid evolution of the software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Richard Stallman, leader of the Free software movement and member of the free software foundation opposes the term open source being applied to what they refer to as free software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Although he agrees that the two terms describe almost the same category of software, Stallman considers equating the terms incorrect and misleading.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] He believes that the main difference is that by choosing one term over the other lets others know about what one's goals are: development (open source) or a social stance (free software).
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Nevertheless, there is significant overlap between open source software and free software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The FSF considers free software to be a subset of open-source software, and Richard Stallman explained that DRM software, for example, can be developed as open source, despite how it restricts its users, and thus does not qualify as free software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The FSF said that the term open source fosters an ambiguity of a different kind such that it confuses the mere availability of the source with the freedom to use, modify, and redistribute it.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] On the other hand, the term free software was criticized for the ambiguity of the word free, which was seen as discouraging for business adoption, and for the historical ambiguous usage of the term.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Developers have used the alternative terms *Free and Open Source Software* (FOSS), or *Free/Libre and Open Source Software* (FLOSS), consequently, to describe open-source software that is also free software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Software can be distributed with source code, which is a code that is readable.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Software is source available when this source code is available to be seen.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However to be source available or FOSS, the source code does not need to be accessible to all, just the users of that software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] While all FOSS software is source available because this is a requirement made by the Open Source Definition, not all source available software is FOSS.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] For example, if the software does not meet other aspects of the Open Source Definition such as permitted modification or redistribution, even if the source code is available, the software is not FOSS.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] A recent trend within software companies is open-sourcing, or transitioning their previous proprietary software into open-source software through releasing it under an open-source license.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Examples of companies who have done this are Google, Microsoft and Apple.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Additionally, open-sourcing can refer to programming open-source software or installing open-source software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Open-sourcing can be beneficial in multiple ways, such as attracting more external contributors who bring new perspectives and problem solving capabilities.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The downsides of open-sourcing include the work that has to be done to maintaining the new community, such as making the base code easily understandable, setting up communication channels for new developers and creating documentation to allow new developers to easily join.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However, a review of several open-sourced projects found that although a newly open-sourced project attracts many newcomers, a great amount are likely to soon leave the project and their forks are also likely to not be impactful.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Other concepts that may share some similarities to open source are shareware, public domain software, freeware, and software viewers/readers that are freely available but do not provide source code.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However, these differ from open source software in access to source code, licensing, copyright and fees.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Despite being able to collaborate internationally, open source software contributors were found to mostly be located in large clusters such as Silicon Valley that largely collaborate within themselves.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Possible reasons for this phenomenon may be that the OSS contributor demographic largely works in software, meaning that the OSS geographic location is closely related to that dispersion and collaborations could be encouraged through work and social networks.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Code acceptance can be impacted by status within these social network clusters, creating unfair predispositions in code acceptance based on location.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Barriers to international collaboration also include linguistic or cultural differences.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Furthermore, each country has been shown to have a higher acceptance rate for code from contributors within their country except India, indicating a bias for culturally similar collaborators.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In 2021, the countries with the highest open source software contributions included the United States, China, Germany, India, and the UK, in that order.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The countries with the highest OSS developers per capita from a study in 2021 include, in order, Iceland, Switzerland, Norway, Sweden, and Finland, while in 2008 the countries with top amount of estimated contributors in SourceForge were the United States, Germany, United Kingdom, Canada and France.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Though there have been several studies done on the distribution and contributions of OSS developers, this is still an open field that can be measured in several different ways.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] For instance, Information and communication technology participation, population, wealth and proportion of access to the internet have been shown to be correlated with OSS contributions.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Although gender diversity has been found to enhance team productivity, women still face biases while contributing to open source software projects when their gender is identifiable.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In 2002, only 1.5% of international open-source software developers were women, while women made up 28% of tech industry roles, demonstrating their low representation in the software field.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However, a more recent figure of female OSS participation internationally calculated across 2005 to 2021 is 9.8%, with most being recent contributors, indicating that female participation may be growing.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Contributors to OSS are motivated by belief in FOSS philosophy, personal interests, caring about the community, interest in projects and problem-solving, etc.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] In addition, users of a given software may also contribute as a way of improving tools they use, while others are drawn to the collaborative nature of open-source development environments.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Also, engagement with active projects allow contributors to stay current with industry practices and emerging trends.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The open source projects include the innovations and trends and they make it popular within the tech field.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Contributing to OSS can also increase a contributor's visibility and reputation within the community, as contributions are publicly accessible and can be reviewed by others.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] As a result, thousands of contributors daily contribute to the open source projects and help maintain it for the improvement of general public.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Even though programming was originally seen as a female profession, there remains a large gap in computing.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Social identity tends to be a large concern as women in the tech industry face insecurity about attracting unwanted male attention and harassment or being unfeminine in their technology knowledge, having a large impact on confidence.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Some male tech participants make clear that they believe women fitting in within the culture is impossible, furthering the insecurity for women and their place in the tech industry.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Additionally, even in a voluntary contribution environment like open source software, women tend to end up doing the less technical aspects of projects, such as manual testing or documentation despite women and men showing the same productivity in OSS contributions.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Explicit biases include longer feedback time, more scrutinization of code and lower acceptance rate of code.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Specifically in the open-source software community, women report that sexually offensive language is common and the women's identity as female is given more attention that as an OSS contributor.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Bias is hard to address due to the belief that gender should not matter, with most contributors feeling that women getting special treatment is unfair and success should be dependent on skill, preventing any changes to be more inclusive.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Open source software projects are built and maintained by a network of programmers, who may often be volunteers, and are widely used in free as well as commercial products.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] While the term open source applied originally only to the source code of software, it is now being applied to many other areas such as open-source ecology, a movement to decentralize technologies so that any human can use them.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] However, it is often misapplied to other areas that have different and competing principles, which overlap only partially.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The same principles that underlie open-source software can be found in many other ventures, such as open source, open content, and open collaboration.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] This "culture" or ideology takes the view that the principles apply more generally to facilitate concurrent input of different agendas, approaches, and priorities, in contrast with more centralized models of development such as those typically used in commercial companies.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] More than 90 percent of companies use open-source software as a component of their proprietary software.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] The decision to use open-source software, or even engage with open-source projects to improve existing open-source software, is typically a pragmatic business decision.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] When proprietary software is in direct competition with an open-source alternative, research has found conflicting results on the effect of the competition on the proprietary product's price and quality.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] For decades, some companies have made servicing of an open-source software product for enterprise users their business model.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] These companies control an open-source software product, and instead of charging for licensing or use, charge for improvements, integration, and other servicing.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Software as a service (SaaS) products based on open-source components are increasingly common.
[src:supabase-platform/open-source-software] Open-source software is preferred for scientific applications, because it increases transparency and aids in the validation and acceptance of scientific results.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The PostgreSQL Global Development Group focuses only on developing a database engine and closely related components.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This core is, technically, what comprises PostgreSQL itself, but there is an extensive developer community and ecosystem that provides other important feature sets that might, traditionally, be provided by a proprietary software vendor.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] These include special-purpose database engine features, like those needed to support a geospatial or temporal database or features which emulate other database products.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Also available from third parties are a wide variety of user and machine interface features, such as graphical user interfaces or load balancing and high availability toolsets.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The large third-party PostgreSQL support network of people, companies, products, and projects, even though not part of The PostgreSQL Development Group, are essential to the PostgreSQL database engine's adoption and use and make up the PostgreSQL ecosystem writ large.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL was originally named POSTGRES, referring to its origins as a successor to the Ingres database developed at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] After a review in 2007, the development team decided to keep the name PostgreSQL and the alias Postgres.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL evolved from the Ingres project at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In 1982, the leader of the Ingres team, Michael Stonebraker, left Berkeley to make a proprietary version of Ingres.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] He returned to Berkeley in 1985, and began a post-Ingres project to address the problems with contemporary database systems that had become increasingly clear during the early 1980s.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] He won the Turing Award in 2014 for these and other projects, and techniques pioneered in them.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The new project, POSTGRES, aimed to add the fewest features needed to completely support data types.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] These features included the ability to define types and to fully describe relationships – something used widely, but maintained entirely by the user.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In POSTGRES, the database understood relationships, and could retrieve information in related tables in a natural way using *rules*.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] POSTGRES used many of the ideas of Ingres, but not its code.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Starting in 1986, published papers described the basis of the system, and a prototype version was shown at the 1988 ACM SIGMOD Conference.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The team released version 1 to a small number of users in June 1989, followed by version 2 with a re-written rules system in June 1990.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Version 3, released in 1991, again re-wrote the rules system, and added support for multiple storage managers and an improved query engine.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] By 1993, the number of users began to overwhelm the project with requests for support and features.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] After releasing version 4.2 on June 30, 1994 – primarily a cleanup – the project ended.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Berkeley released POSTGRES under an MIT License variant, which enabled other developers to use the code for any use.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] At the time, POSTGRES used an Ingres-influenced POSTQUEL query language interpreter, which could be interactively used with a console application named monitor.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In 1994, Berkeley graduate students Andrew Yu and Jolly Chen replaced the POSTQUEL query language interpreter with one for the SQL query language, creating Postgres95.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The monitor console was also replaced by psql.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Yu and Chen announced the first version (0.01) to beta testers on May 5, 1995.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Version 1.0 of Postgres95 was announced on September 5, 1995, with a more liberal license that enabled the software to be freely modifiable.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] On July 8, 1996, Marc Fournier at Hub.org Networking Services provided the first non-university development server for the open-source development effort.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] With the participation of Bruce Momjian and Vadim B.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Mikheev, work began to stabilize the code inherited from Berkeley.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed to PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The online presence at the website PostgreSQL.org began on October 22, 1996.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The first PostgreSQL release formed version 6.0 on January 29, 1997.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Since then developers and volunteers around the world have maintained the software as The PostgreSQL Global Development Group.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The project continues to make releases available under its free and open-source software PostgreSQL License.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Code comes from contributions from proprietary vendors, support companies, and open-source programmers.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] As of 2025, PostgreSQL is on major release version 18 which is notable in implementing asynchronous I/O (AIO), enabling database users to perform concurrent I/O tasks like readahead and sequential scan.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages concurrency through multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), which gives each transaction a "snapshot" of the database, allowing changes to be made without affecting other transactions.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This largely eliminates the need for read locks, and ensures the database maintains ACID principles.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL offers four levels of transaction isolation: Read Uncommitted, Read Committed, Repeatable Read and Serializable.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Because PostgreSQL is immune to dirty reads, requesting a Read Uncommitted transaction isolation level provides read committed instead.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports full serializability via the serializable snapshot isolation (SSI) method.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The PostgreSQL MVCC implementation is prone to performance issues that require tuning when under a heavy write load which updates existing rows.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in binary replication based on shipping the changes (write-ahead logs (WAL)) to replica nodes asynchronously, with the ability to run read-only queries against these replicated nodes.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This allows splitting read traffic among multiple nodes efficiently.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Earlier replication software that allowed similar read scaling normally relied on adding replication triggers to the master, increasing load.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in synchronous replication that ensures that, for each write transaction, the master waits until at least one replica node has written the data to its transaction log.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Unlike other database systems, the durability of a transaction (whether it is asynchronous or synchronous) can be specified per-database, per-user, per-session or even per-transaction.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This can be useful for workloads that do not require such guarantees, and may not be wanted for all data as it slows down performance due to the requirement of the confirmation of the transaction reaching the synchronous standby.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Standby servers can be synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Synchronous standby servers can be specified in the configuration which determines which servers are candidates for synchronous replication.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The first in the list that is actively streaming will be used as the current synchronous server.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] When this fails, the system fails over to the next in line.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL's replication can trigger conflicts between the primary and standby servers, particularly whenever tuples are prematurely deleted from the standby server despite ongoing queries accessing them.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] To address this, PostgreSQL includes a feedback flag where the standby server proactively informs the primary server of any ongoing queries to mitigate this type of conflict.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Synchronous multi-master replication is not included in the PostgreSQL core.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Postgres-XC which is based on PostgreSQL provides scalable synchronous multi-master replication.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] It is licensed under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] A related project is called Postgres-XL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Bidirectional replication (BDR) is an asynchronous multi-master replication system for PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Tools such as repmgr make managing replication clusters easier.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Several asynchronous trigger-based replication packages are available.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in support for regular B-tree and hash table indexes, and four index access methods: generalized search trees (GiST), generalized inverted indexes (GIN), Space-Partitioned GiST (SP-GiST) and Block Range Indexes (BRIN).
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In addition, user-defined index methods can be created, although this is quite an involved process.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL schemas are namespaces, allowing objects of the same kind and name to co-exist in a single database.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] They are not to be confused with a database schema—the abstract, structural, organizational specification which defines how every table's data relates to data within other tables.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] All PostgreSQL database objects, except for a few global objects such as roles and tablespaces, exist within a schema.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] They cannot be nested, schemas cannot contain schemas.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The permission system controls access to schemas and their content.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] By default, newly created databases have only a single schema called *public* but other schemas can be added and the public schema isn't mandatory.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] A `search_path` setting determines the order in which PostgreSQL checks schemas for unqualified objects (those without a prefixed schema).
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] By default, it is set to `$user, public` (`$user` refers to the currently connected database user).
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This default can be set on a database or role level, but as it is a session parameter, it can be freely changed (even multiple times) during a client session, affecting that session only.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Non-existent schemas, or other schemas not accessible to the logged-in user, that are listed in search_path are silently skipped during object lookup.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] New objects are created in whichever valid schema (one that can be accessed) appears first in the search_path.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In addition, users can create their own data types which can usually be made fully indexable via PostgreSQL's indexing infrastructures – GiST, GIN, SP-GiST.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Examples of these include the geographic information system (GIS) data types from the PostGIS project for PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] There is also a data type called a *domain*, which is the same as any other data type but with optional constraints defined by the creator of that domain.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This means any data entered into a column using the domain will have to conform to whichever constraints were defined as part of the domain.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] A data type that represents a range of data can be used which are called range types.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] These can be discrete ranges (e.g. all integer values 1 to 10) or continuous ranges (e.g., any time between 10:00 am and 11:00 am).
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The built-in range types available include ranges of integers, big integers, decimal numbers, time stamps (with and without time zone) and dates.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Custom range types can be created to make new types of ranges available, such as IP address ranges using the inet type as a base, or float ranges using the float data type as a base.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Range types support inclusive and exclusive range boundaries using the [] and () characters respectively.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] (e.g., `[4,9)` represents all integers starting from and including 4 up to but not including 9.) Range types are also compatible with existing operators used to check for overlap, containment, right of etc.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Tables can be set to inherit their characteristics from a *parent* table.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Data in child tables will appear to exist in the parent tables, unless data is selected from the parent table using the ONLY keyword, i.e.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Adding a column in the parent table will cause that column to appear in the child table.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Inheritance can be used to implement table partitioning, using either triggers or rules to direct inserts to the parent table into the proper child tables.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In particular, table constraints are not currently inheritable.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] All check constraints and not-null constraints on a parent table are automatically inherited by its children.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Other types of constraints (unique, primary key, and foreign key constraints) are not inherited.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Inheritance provides a way to map the features of generalization hierarchies depicted in entity–relationship diagrams (ERDs) directly into the PostgreSQL database.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL can link to other systems to retrieve data via foreign data wrappers (FDWs).
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] These can take the form of any data source, such as a file system, another relational database management system (RDBMS), or a web service.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This means that regular database queries can use these data sources like regular tables, and even join multiple data-sources together.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports a binary communication protocol that allows applications to connect to the database server.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The protocol is versioned (currently 3.0, as of PostgreSQL 7.4) and has a detailed specification.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The official client implementation of this communication protocol is a C API, libpq.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In addition, the officially supported ECPG tool allows SQL commands to be embedded in C code.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Both are part of the standard PostgreSQL distribution.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Third-party libraries for connecting to PostgreSQL are available for many programming languages, including C++, Java, Julia, Python, Node.js, Go, and Rust.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Procedural languages allow developers to extend the database with custom subroutines (functions), often called *stored procedures*.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] These functions can be used to build database triggers (functions invoked on modification of certain data) and custom data types and aggregate functions.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Procedural languages can also be invoked without defining a function, using a DO command at SQL level.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Languages are divided into two groups: Procedures written in *safe* languages are sandboxed and can be safely created and used by any user.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Procedures written in *unsafe* languages can only be created by superusers, because they allow bypassing a database's security restrictions, but can also access sources external to the database.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Some languages like Perl provide both safe and unsafe versions.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In addition, PostgreSQL allows procedural languages to be loaded into the database through extensions.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Three language extensions are included with PostgreSQL to support Perl, Tcl, and Python.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] For Python, the current Python 3 is used, and the discontinued Python 2 is no longer supported as of PostgreSQL 15.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Both were supported previously, defaulting to Python 2, while old and new versions couldn't be used in the same session.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] External projects provide support for many other languages, including PL/Java, JavaScript (PL/V8), PL/Julia, PL/R, PL/Ruby, and others.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Triggers are events triggered by the action of SQL data manipulation language (DML) statements.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] For example, an INSERT statement might activate a trigger that checks if the values of the statement are valid.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Most triggers are only activated by either INSERT or UPDATE statements.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Triggers are fully supported and can be attached to tables.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Triggers can be per-column and conditional, in that UPDATE triggers can target specific columns of a table, and triggers can be told to execute under a set of conditions as specified in the trigger's WHERE clause.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Triggers can be attached to views by using the INSTEAD OF condition.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Multiple triggers are fired in alphabetical order.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In addition to calling functions written in the native PL/pgSQL, triggers can also invoke functions written in other languages like PL/Python or PL/Perl.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL provides an asynchronous messaging system that is accessed through the NOTIFY, LISTEN and UNLISTEN commands.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] A session can issue a NOTIFY command, along with the user-specified channel and an optional payload, to mark a particular event occurring.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Other sessions are able to detect these events by issuing a LISTEN command, which can listen to a particular channel.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This functionality can be used for a wide variety of purposes, such as letting other sessions know when a table has updated or for separate applications to detect when a particular action has been performed.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Such a system prevents the need for continuous polling by applications to see if anything has yet changed, and reducing unnecessary overhead.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Notifications are fully transactional, in that messages are not sent until the transaction they were sent from is committed.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This eliminates the problem of messages being sent for an action being performed which is then rolled back.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Many connectors for PostgreSQL provide support for this notification system (including libpq, JDBC, Npgsql, psycopg and node.js) so it can be used by external applications.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL can act as an effective, persistent "pub/sub" server or job server by combining LISTEN with FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Rules allow the "query tree" of an incoming query to be rewritten; they are an, automatically invoked, macro language for SQL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] "Query Re-Write Rules" are attached to a table/class and "Re-Write" the incoming DML (select, insert, update, and/or delete) into one or more queries that either replace the original DML statement or execute in addition to it.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Query Re-Write occurs after DML statement parsing and before query planning.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The functionality rules provide was, in almost every way, later duplicated with the introduction of newer types of triggers.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The use of triggers is usually preferred over rules as it is easier to reason about trigger behavior and interactions than when equivalent rules are used.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL server is process-based (not threaded), and uses one operating system process per database session.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Multiple sessions are automatically spread across all available CPUs by the operating system.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Many types of queries can also be parallelized across multiple background worker processes, taking advantage of multiple CPUs or cores.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Client applications can use threads and create multiple database connections from each thread.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages its internal security on a per-role basis.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] A role is generally regarded to be a user (a role that can log in), or a group (a role of which other roles are members).
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Permissions can be granted or revoked on any object down to the column level, and can allow or prevent the visibility/creation/alteration/deletion of objects at the database, schema, table, and row levels.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL's SECURITY LABEL feature (extension to SQL standards), allows for additional security; with a bundled loadable module that supports label-based mandatory access control (MAC) based on Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) security policy.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The GSSAPI, SSPI, Kerberos, peer, ident and certificate methods can also use a specified "map" file that lists which users matched by that authentication system are allowed to connect as a specific database user.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] These methods are specified in the cluster's host-based authentication configuration file (pg_hba.conf), which determines what connections are allowed.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This allows control over which user can connect to which database, where they can connect from (IP address, IP address range, domain socket), which authentication system will be enforced, and whether the connection must use Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL claims high, but not complete, conformance with the latest SQL standard ("as of the version 17 release in September 2024, PostgreSQL conforms to at least 170 of the 177 mandatory features for SQL:2023 Core conformance", and no other databases fully conformed to it).
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] One exception is the handling of unquoted identifiers like table or column names.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In PostgreSQL they are folded, internally, to lower case characters whereas the standard says that unquoted identifiers should be folded to upper case.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Thus, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO` not `foo` according to the standard.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Other shortcomings concern the absence of temporal tables allowing automatic logging of row versions during transactions with the possibility of browsing in time (FOR SYSTEM TIME predicate), although relatively SQL compliant third-party extensions are available.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Many informal performance studies of PostgreSQL have been done.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Performance improvements aimed at improving scalability began heavily with version 8.1.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Simple benchmarks between version 8.0 and version 8.4 showed that the latter was more than ten times faster on read-only workloads and at least 7.5 times faster on both read and write workloads.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The first industry-standard and peer-validated benchmark was completed in June 2007, using the Sun Java System Application Server (proprietary version of GlassFish) 9.0 Platform Edition, UltraSPARC T1-based Sun Fire server and PostgreSQL 8.2.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This result of 778.14 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard compares favourably with the 874 JOPS@Standard with Oracle 10 on an Itanium-based HP-UX system.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In August 2007, Sun submitted an improved benchmark score of 813.73 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] With the system under test at a reduced price, the price/performance improved from $84.98/JOPS to $70.57/JOPS.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The default configuration of PostgreSQL uses only a small amount of dedicated memory for performance-critical purposes such as caching database blocks and sorting.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This limitation is primarily because older operating systems required kernel changes to allow allocating large blocks of shared memory.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL.org provides advice on basic recommended performance practice in a wiki.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In April 2012, Robert Haas of EnterpriseDB demonstrated PostgreSQL 9.2's linear CPU scalability using a server with 64 cores.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Matloob Khushi performed benchmarking between PostgreSQL 9.0 and MySQL 5.6.15 for their ability to process genomic data.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In his performance analysis he found that PostgreSQL extracts overlapping genomic regions eight times faster than MySQL using two datasets of 80,000 each forming random human DNA regions.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Insertion and data uploads in PostgreSQL were also better, although general searching ability of both databases was almost equivalent.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] 64-bit Power ISA), SPARC (also 64-bit), MIPS and PA-RISC.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] It was also known to work on some other platforms (while not been tested on for years, i.e. for latest versions).
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] , which can be used to enter SQL queries directly, or execute them from a file.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] In addition, psql provides a number of meta-commands and various shell-like features to facilitate writing scripts and automating a wide variety of tasks; for example tab completion of object names and SQL syntax.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] (GUI) administration tool for PostgreSQL, which is supported on many computer platforms.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The program is available in more than a dozen languages.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The second incarnation (named pgAdmin II) was a complete rewrite, first released on January 16, 2002.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] and then released under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] framework allowing it to run on most common operating systems.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The query tool includes a scripting language called pgScript for supporting admin and development tasks.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] announced that with the shift towards web-based models, work has begun on pgAdmin 4 with the aim to facilitate cloud deployments.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to perform essential PostgreSQL database development tasks from a web-based console.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] PostgreSQL Studio allows users to work with cloud databases without the need to open firewalls.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] AJAX/JavaScript-driven web interface for PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Allows browsing, maintaining and creating data and database objects via a web browser.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] management for commonly used scripts, among other features.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Installers are available for Windows, Macintosh, and Linux, and a simple cross-platform archive that runs from a script.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Base can be used as a front-end for PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] The pgBadger PostgreSQL log analyzer generates detailed reports from a PostgreSQL log file.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] pgDevOps is a suite of web tools to install & manage multiple PostgreSQL versions, extensions, and community components, develop SQL queries, monitor running databases and find performance problems.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] is a simple web-based administration tool for PostgreSQL and others, written in PHP.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] pgBackRest is a backup and restore tool for PostgreSQL that provides support for full, differential, and incremental backups.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] pgaudit is a PostgreSQL extension that provides detailed session and/or object audit logging via the standard logging facility provided by PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Postgresus is an open source backup tool with GUI for scheduled backups with support of external sources (S3, NAS, FTP, Google Drive, Google Cloud, etc.) and notifications to external services (Slack, Discord, Telegram, SMTP, etc.).
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] A number of companies offer proprietary tools for PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] They often consist of a universal core that is adapted for various specific database products.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] These tools mostly share the administration features with the open source tools but offer improvements in data modeling, importing, exporting or reporting.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] Due to its permissive open-source license and extensible architecture, a broad ecosystem has developed around PostgreSQL.
[src:supabase-platform/postgresql] This includes numerous companies offering dedicated support and hosting, as well as several forks and derivative databases that adapt PostgreSQL for specific workloads.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:supabase-platform/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] A **data control language** (**DCL**) is a syntax similar to a computer programming language used to control access to data stored in a database (authorization).
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] In particular, it is a component of Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] Data Control Language is one of the logical groups in SQL Commands.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] SQL is the standard language for relational database management systems.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] SQL statements are used to perform tasks such as insert data to a database, delete or update data in a database, or retrieve data from a database.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] Though database systems use SQL, they also have their own additional proprietary extensions that are usually only used on their system.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] For example, Microsoft SQL server uses Transact-SQL (T-SQL), which is an extension of SQL.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] Similarly, Oracle uses PL-SQL, which an Oracle-specific SQL extension.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] However, the standard SQL commands such as "Select", "Insert", "Update", "Delete", "Create", and "Drop" can be used to accomplish almost everything that one needs to do with a database.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] The operations for which privileges may be granted to or revoked from a user or role apply to both the Data definition language (DDL) and the Data manipulation language (DML), and may include CONNECT, SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, EXECUTE, and USAGE.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] DCL commands are used for access control and permission management for users in the database.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] With them we can easily allow or deny some actions for users on the tables or records (row level security).
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] denies a specified permission to a security object.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] For example: GRANT can be used to give privileges to user to do SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE and DELETE on a specific table or multiple tables.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] The REVOKE command is used to take a privilege away (default) or revoking specific command like UPDATE or DELETE based on requirements.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] In the first example, GRANT gives privileges to user User1 to do SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE and DELETE on the table named Employees.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] In the second example, REVOKE removes User1's privileges to use the INSERT command on the table Employees.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] Oracle Database divide SQL commands to different types.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] So Oracle Database DDL commands include the **Grant** and **Revoke** privileges which is actually part of Data control Language in Microsoft SQL server.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] Transaction control statements manage changes made by DML statements.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] The **Grant** and **Revoke** statements are part of Account Management Statements.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] The GRANT statement enables system administrators to grant privileges and roles, which can be granted to user accounts and roles.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] The REVOKE statement enables system administrators to revoke privileges and roles, which can be revoked from user accounts and roles.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] In PostgreSQL, executing DCL is transactional, and can be rolled back.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] SQLite does not have any DCL commands as it does not have usernames or logins.
[src:supabase-platform/row-level-security] Instead, SQLite depends on file-system permissions to define who can open and access a database.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] WebSocket is distinct from HTTP used to serve most webpages.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Although they are different, RFC 6455 states that WebSocket "is designed to work over HTTP ports 443 and 80 as well as to support HTTP proxies and intermediaries", making the WebSocket protocol compatible with HTTP.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] To achieve compatibility, the WebSocket handshake uses the HTTP Upgrade header to change from the HTTP protocol to the WebSocket protocol.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The WebSocket protocol enables full-duplex interaction between a web browser (or other client application) and a web server with lower overhead than half-duplex alternatives such as HTTP polling, facilitating real-time data transfer from and to the server.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] This is achieved by providing a standardized way for the server to send content to the client without being first requested by the client, and allowing messages to be exchanged while keeping the connection open.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] In this way, a two-way ongoing conversation can take place between the client and the server.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The communications are usually done over TCP port number 443 (or 80 in the case of unsecured connections), which is beneficial for environments that block non-web Internet connections using a firewall.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Additionally, WebSocket enables streams of messages on top of TCP.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] TCP alone deals with streams of bytes with no inherent concept of a message.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Similar two-way browser–server communications have been achieved in non-standardized ways using stopgap technologies such as Comet or Adobe Flash Player.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Most browsers support the protocol, including Google Chrome, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Internet Explorer, Safari and Opera.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The WebSocket protocol specification defines `ws` (WebSocket) and `wss` (WebSocket Secure) as two new uniform resource identifier (URI) schemes that are used for unencrypted and encrypted connections respectively.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Apart from the scheme name and fragment (i.e.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] `#` is not supported), the rest of the URI components are defined to use URI generic syntax.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] WebSocket was first referenced as TCPConnection in the HTML5 specification, as a placeholder for a TCP-based socket API.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] In June 2008, a series of discussions were led by Michael Carter that resulted in the first version of the protocol known as WebSocket.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Before WebSocket, port 80 full-duplex communication was attainable using Comet channels; however, Comet implementation is nontrivial, and due to the TCP handshake and HTTP header overhead, it is inefficient for small messages.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The WebSocket protocol aims to solve these problems without compromising the security assumptions of the web.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The name "WebSocket" was coined by Ian Hickson and Michael Carter shortly thereafter through collaboration on the #whatwg IRC chat room, and subsequently authored for inclusion in the HTML5 specification by Ian Hickson.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] In December 2009, Google Chrome 4 was the first browser to ship full support for the standard, with WebSocket enabled by default.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Development of the WebSocket protocol was subsequently moved from the W3C and WHATWG group to the IETF in February 2010, and authored for two revisions under Ian Hickson.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] After the protocol was shipped and enabled by default in multiple browsers, the RFC 6455 was finalized under Ian Fette in December 2011.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] RFC 7692 introduced compression extension to WebSocket using the DEFLATE algorithm on a per-message basis.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] A web application (e.g. web browser) may use the `WebSocket` interface to maintain bidirectional communications with a WebSocket server.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] **Frame-based message** exchange: data, ping and pong messages.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] **Closing handshake**: close message (request then echoed in response).
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The client sends an **HTTP request** (**method** **GET**, **version ≥ 1.1**) and the server returns an **HTTP response** with **status code 101** (*Switching Protocols*) on success.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] HTTP and WebSocket clients can connect to a server using the same port because the opening handshake uses HTTP.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Sending additional HTTP headers (that are not in the table below) is allowed.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] After the *Switching Protocols* HTTP response, the opening handshake is complete, the HTTP protocol stops being used, and communication switches to a binary frame-based protocol.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The following Python code generates a random `Sec-WebSocket-Key`.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The following Python code calculates `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` using `Sec-WebSocket-Key` from the example request above.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] `Sec-WebSocket-Key` and `Sec-WebSocket-Accept` are intended to prevent a caching proxy from re-sending a previous WebSocket conversation, and does not provide any authentication, privacy, or integrity.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Though some servers accept a short `Sec-WebSocket-Key`, many modern servers will reject the request with error "invalid Sec-WebSocket-Key header".
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] After the opening handshake, the client and server can, at any time, send **data messages** (text or binary) and **control messages** (*Close*, *Ping*, *Pong*) to each other.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] A message is composed of **one frame if unfragmented** or **at least two frames if fragmented**.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] A **client must mask** all frames sent to the server.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] A **server must not mask** any frames sent to the client.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Frame masking applies **XOR between the payload and the masking key**.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The following pseudocode describes the algorithm used to both mask and unmask a frame.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The `permessage-deflate` extension allows data messages to be compressed using the DEFLATE algorithm.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] For example, during the opening handshake, the client and server may use the following header to enable the extension.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The `RSV1` field of the first frame of a data message must be set to indicate the payload data is compressed.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Note: `recv()` returns up to the amount of bytes requested.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] For readability, the code ignores that, thus it may fail in non-ideal network conditions.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] A secure version of the WebSocket protocol is implemented in Firefox 6, Safari 6, Google Chrome 14, Opera 12.10 and Internet Explorer 10.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] A detailed protocol test suite report lists the conformance of those browsers to specific protocol aspects.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] An older, less secure version of the protocol was implemented in Opera 11 and Safari 5, as well as the mobile version of Safari in iOS 4.2.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The BlackBerry Browser in OS7 implements WebSockets.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Because of vulnerabilities, it was disabled in Firefox 4 and 5, and Opera 11.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Using browser developer tools, developers can inspect the WebSocket handshake as well as the WebSocket frames.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] ASP.NET Core have support for WebSockets using the `app.UseWebSockets();` middleware.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Unlike regular cross-domain HTTP requests, WebSocket requests are not restricted by the same-origin policy.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] It is better to use tokens or similar protection mechanisms to authenticate the WebSocket connection when sensitive (private) data is being transferred over the WebSocket.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] A live example of vulnerability was seen in 2020 in the form of Cable Haunt.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] WebSocket protocol client implementations try to detect whether the user agent is configured to use a proxy when connecting to destination host and port, and if it is, uses HTTP CONNECT method to set up a persistent tunnel.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] The WebSocket protocol is unaware of proxy servers and firewalls.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Some proxy servers are transparent and work fine with WebSocket; others will prevent WebSocket from working correctly, causing the connection to fail.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] In some cases, additional proxy-server configuration may be required, and certain proxy servers may need to be upgraded to support WebSocket.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] If unencrypted WebSocket traffic flows through an explicit or a transparent proxy server without WebSockets support, the connection will likely fail.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] If an encrypted WebSocket connection is used, then the use of Transport Layer Security (TLS) in the WebSocket Secure connection ensures that an `HTTP CONNECT` command is issued when the browser is configured to use an explicit proxy server.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] This sets up a tunnel, which provides low-level end-to-end TCP communication through the HTTP proxy, between the WebSocket Secure client and the WebSocket server.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] In the case of transparent proxy servers, the browser is unaware of the proxy server, so no `HTTP CONNECT` is sent.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] However, since the wire traffic is encrypted, intermediate transparent proxy servers may simply allow the encrypted traffic through, so there is a much better chance that the WebSocket connection will succeed if WebSocket Secure is used.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] Using encryption is not free of resource cost, but often provides the highest success rate, since it would be travelling through a secure tunnel.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] A mid-2010 draft (version hixie-76) broke compatibility with reverse proxies and gateways by including eight bytes of key data after the headers, but not advertising that data in a `Content-Length: 8` header.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] This data was not forwarded by all intermediates, which could lead to protocol failure.
[src:supabase-platform/websocket] More recent drafts (e.g., hybi-09) put the key data in a `Sec-WebSocket-Key` header, solving this problem.
